Milestone 1

Problem Definition¶

The context: Why is this problem important to solve?

  • It is necessary to diagnose patients with malaria early in order to get them quick treatment to prevent fatalities. Through quick diagnoses, we can solve countless lives by providing treatment to patients with malaria before it becomes far too late.

The objectives: What is the intended goal?

  • We want to build a machine learning model that can accurately determine if a cell has been infected by a parasite or not given a picture of the cell. By creating an efficient and accurate model, we hope to easily determine if a cell has been infected by Plasmodium parasites to determine whether or not a patient needs treatment for malaria. We also hope to reduce the need for human expertise in diagnosing malaria by tasking a computer to perform diagnosing.

The key questions: What are the key questions that need to be answered?

  • What key features distinguish a healthy cell with minor blemishes from an infected cell?
  • How can we minimize the effect of natural inaccuracies when viewing healthy cells?
  • How can we determine between the natural blemishes of normal cells and the ones caused by the parasite infection?

The problem formulation: What is it that we are trying to solve using data science?

  • Using data science, we want to be able to distinguish between uninfected and parasitized cells so that we can diagnose patients with malaria. We want to be able to quickly diagnose malaria-infected cells without the need for human dependency, which may lead to inaccurate results.

Data Description ¶

There are a total of 24,958 train and 2,600 test images (colored) that we have taken from microscopic images. These images are of the following categories:

Parasitized: The parasitized cells contain the Plasmodium parasite which causes malaria
Uninfected: The uninfected cells are free of the Plasmodium parasites

The extracted folder has different folders for train and test data which further contains the different sizes of images for parasitized and uninfected cells within the respective folder name.

The size of all images must be the same and should be converted to 4D arrays so that they can be used as an input for the convolutional neural network. Also, we need to create the labels for both types of images to be able to train and test the model.

Let's do the same for the training data first and then we will use the same code for the test data as well.

In [6]:
#Storing the path of the extracted "train" folder 
train_dir = '/content/cell_images/train'

#Size of image so that each image has the same size
SIZE = 64

#Empty list to store the training images after they are converted to NumPy arrays
train_images = []

#Empty list to store the training labels (0 - uninfected, 1 - parasitized)
train_labels = []
In [7]:
#We will run the same code for "parasitized" as well as "uninfected" folders within the "train" folder
for folder_name in ['/parasitized/', '/uninfected/']:
    
    #Path of the folder
    images_path = os.listdir(train_dir + folder_name)

    for i, image_name in enumerate(images_path):
        try:
            #Opening each image using the path of that image
            image = Image.open(train_dir + folder_name + image_name)

            #Resizing each image to (64,64)
            image = image.resize((SIZE, SIZE))

            #Converting images to arrays and appending that array to the empty list defined above
            train_images.append(np.array(image))

            #Creating labels for parasitized and uninfected images
            if folder_name=='/parasitized/':
                train_labels.append(1)
            else:
                train_labels.append(0)
        except Exception:
            pass       

#Converting lists to arrays
train_images = np.array(train_images)
train_labels = np.array(train_labels)

# function to find the mean
def find_mean_img(full_mat, title):
    # calculate the average
    mean_img = np.mean(full_mat, axis = 0)[0]
    # reshape it back to a matrix
    plt.imshow(mean_img)
    plt.title(f'Average {title}')
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()
    return mean_img

Proposed approach¶

Potential techniques: What different techniques should be explored?

  • We should use a CNN as our model
  • We want to experiment with different layers for our CNN
  • Leaky RELU layers will help us focus on the blemish but too many may eliminate the blemish
  • We can experiment with different numbers of convolutional layers
  • We could potentially incorporate a dropout layer to reduce overfitting if it becomes a problem
  • We will change the number of epochs and the batch size to balance performance and speed

Overall solution design: What is the potential solution design?

  • Preprocess images with gaussian blurring and HSV conversion
  • Gaussian blurring may be helpful as it will eliminate minor noise (blemishes) in our cell images
  • HSV conversion will also be helpful as it will put all images, regardless of background color, to one similar format
  • Since we are dealing with images, we will use a convolutional neural network
  • Leaky RELU layers will help us eliminate unneeded data and only look at the blemish
  • Since we want to ignore minor blemishes, we can look at max pooling for our images to capture only the major details
  • Since we are determining between two options, we want to use a sigmoid activation function for our output layer
  • Other than these, we can add in convolutional layers and a dense layer

Measures of success: What are the key measures of success to compare different techniques?

  • We want to maximize our recall as diagnosing a person who actually has malaria for quick treatment, which will save countless lives, is much more important than reducing false positives, which will result in a minor waste in resources for hospitals. Therefore, we will primarily focus on recall as our main metric when comparing models.

Plotting the train and validation curves

In [50]:
# function to plot train and validation accuracy 
def plot_accuracy(history):
    N = len(history.history["accuracy"])
    plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
    plt.plot(np.arange(0, N), history.history["accuracy"], label="train_accuracy", ls='--')
    plt.plot(np.arange(0, N), history.history["val_accuracy"], label="val_accuracy", ls='--')
    plt.title("Accuracy vs Epoch")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
    plt.legend(loc="upper left")

transfer_layer = vgg.get_layer('block5_pool')
vgg.trainable=False

# Add classification layers on top of it  
 
x = Flatten()(transfer_layer.output) #Flatten the output from the 3rd block of the VGG16 model
x = Dense(256, activation='relu')(x)

# Similarly add a dense layer with 128 neurons
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.3)(x)

# Add a dense layer with 64 neurons
x = Dense(64, activation='relu')(x)

x = BatchNormalization()(x)
pred = Dense(2, activation='softmax')(x)

model4 = Model(vgg.input, pred) #Initializing the model

Think about it:¶

  • What observations and insights can be drawn from the confusion matrix and classification report?
  • Choosw the model with the best accuracy scores from all the above models and save it as a final model.

Observations and Conclusions drawn from the final model:

  • Our final model is model 3 which uses data augmentation
  • Data Augmentation helps by creating new data that can be trained
  • Vast majority of new data retained defining dark spots of parasitized cells
  • Data Augmentation appears to help the recall of our model significantly
  • We can predict parasitized cells with our model at an almost 100% rate
  • We only had 6 false-positives for our cell

Improvements that can be done:

  • Can the model performance be improved using other pre-trained models or different CNN architecture?
  • You can try to build a model using these HSV images and compare them with your other models.

Insights¶

Refined insights:¶

  • What are the most meaningful insights from the data relevant to the problem?
  • Parasitized cells have defining dark spot
  • Regular cells may have gradients of color
  • Data augmentation retains dark spots
  • We can reliably train machine learning models to detect these dark spots in cell images
  • Neural networks can be reliably used to detect malaria in cells

Comparison of various techniques and their relative performance:¶

  • How do different techniques perform? Which one is performing relatively better? Is there scope to improve the performance further?
  • Our modified model outperforms our base model in false negatives but not in false positives
  • The LeakyRELU model is outperforming the base model in both false negatives and false positives but lags behind the modified model
  • The vgg16 model is underperforming for both false positives and false negatives
  • The data augmentation model appears to be performing the best due to its low number of false positives
  • We can improve our performance by doing image preprocessing with Gaussian Blurring and HSV conversion.

Proposal for the final solution design:¶

  • What model do you propose to be adopted? Why is this the best solution to adopt?
  • We will use model 3 which incorporates data augmentation for the model. It is the best solution because it gives us the highest recall rate of ~100% and the lowest number of false negatives (6), which is what we are trying to avoid.
